Energy generator KenGen has ended a two-year dividend dry spell, awarding investors Sh0.40 per share. This despite the firm's profits for the year ended June 30, 2018, dropping 12.4 per cent to Sh7.89 billion from Sh9.01 billion last year. Revenues for the year under review rose 4.3 per cent to Sh45.29 billion. However, operating profits dipped 15.6 per cent to Sh11.44 billion on account of massive investments in geothermal projects. "We remained resilient in turbulent waters during the year under review marred with a drop in water levels and heightened political activities," KengGen managing director Rebecca Miano said. Click here for the latest political news 